  The reason why some cds (data) cannot be copied is that the burner is not capable of reproducing the exact CD. Most writers are like that. In the end of 2000 (I think), they implemented cd protection level 1, then followed level 2.. and rescently a new level has been placed (not sure about it though). It consists of patterns that an generic writer and generic burning ware cannot reproduce. Originally it was a volontary set of errors placed in the CD data. If the program doesnt see this pattern it won't start.<br>
<br>
  But there's a limit to this. We still need to be able to read the legitimate CD!! All CD-roms need to be able to see this protection, and read the CD correctly. Thats why cds can be still copied perfectly by certain quality burners, assisted by appropriate software. They just need to be able to write just as good as they can read.<br>
<br>
   As for music CDs, theres nothing worse and single-minded than a conventional music-CD device. A CD-player doesnt do anything else but make the CD spin and expect 0s and 1s, translating it to sound waves. Its certainly not designed for any encoding and even less, protection. This technology is easely compared to bumps and holes on a .. well those round, black plastic disks. Its so easy, burners have a very easy time writing them, the only challenge being the speed. To prevent us from copying, they'd need to change all the CD players... making them as complex as MP3 players.<br>
<br>
   I hope we're not going back to this. We got free... theres no way im becoming a slave again.<br>
